  Key Risks & Gotchas

  1. cb_sq must hold full block — sequential helpers (square, reduce_row) cannot pipeline since both own all 3 TRISCs. The intermediate CB must hold all shard_W_tiles tiles.
  2. Scaler packing format — The 1/W scaler for reduce<SUM, ROW> needs to be a tile with the value packed in specific positions. Use generate_bcast_unpad_scalar or equivalent packing utility.
  3. Column-vector broadcast — inv_rms is a column vector (one value per tile-row). The final multiply must use bcast_col semantics (mul_tiles_bcast<BcastType::COL>), not element-wise mul.
  4. Multicast when C=1 — Skip the entire all-gather phase. Guard with if (num_cores_in_row > 1).
  5. Input read twice — Block-sharded data lives in L1, so re-reading is cheap (L1→L1). No DRAM round-trip.
  6. Deadlock risk — All cores in a row multicast simultaneously. The receive CB (cb_remote_partials) must be pre-allocated with enough space for all C tiles before any core starts writing. Semaphore must be initialized to 0 before the loop.
  7. noc_async_write_multicast vs _loopback_src — A core should NOT include itself in the multicast destination range. Write its own partial locally instead, or use _loopback_src if self is in the range.
  8. Epsilon addition — After computing mean(x²), add ε before rsqrt, not after. Common mistake.

